president roh taewoo was quoted as 
saying monday that he wants to resolve politically the controversy 
raging over his predecessor chun doohwan an indication he may 
pardon chun 
chun is preparing to apologize for corruption and other misdeeds 
before moving into rural exile 
roh said his government hopes to resolve the controversy over 
chun by the end of this year the former president is being forced 
out of the capital seoul by militant students who rioted and tried 
to break into his home demanding that he be arrested and punished 
for alleged corruption and other abuses during seven years of 
authoritarian rule 
roh was quoted as saying in an interview with the national daily 
shinmun a progovernment newspaper published in seoul 
in handling past wrongdoings a clear distinction must be made 
between those wrongdoings to be dealt with judicially and those to 
be dealt with politically any wrongdoings by chun as chief 
executive of the country should be dealt with politically and there 
should not be political reprisal against the former chief executive 
 
i will take actions under the principle that any wrongdoings by 
a chief executive should be dealt with politically and that any 
political reprisal would only hurt democratic development 
he made the remarks as the 56yearold chun reportedly was 
preparing to make a nationally televised apology wednesday 
newspapers said chun also is to turn over most of his wealth to 
the government and accept rural exile a traditional way of 
repentance for a disgraced korean 
chun originally planned to leave seoul on tuesday but was 
delayed because of difficulty finding him a safe rural home news 
reports said 
the former president who stepped down in february denies 
personal wrongdoing however about a dozen of his relatives and 
associates were convicted or charged with corruption involving 
millions of dollars in public funds 
chun needs a refuge from attack some reports said he would go to 
a mountainside buddhist temple near an army unit in the north 
others said he might move to central south korea he reportedly is 
unwelcome in his southern hometown 
national assembly hearings monday on abuses under the chun 
government focused on attempts to stifle press freedom more than 
700 journalists were fired under government pressure and many 
newspapers and broadcast operations were merged and placed under 
state control by chuns administration 
in recent weeks chun has been a virtual prisoner in his 
luxurious seoul home guarded by hundreds of riot police to prevent 
attacks by dissidents 
rohs government has been accused of trying to protect chun and 
is trying to defuse public anger without being implicated in the 
furor 
chun a former army general took power with military backing in 
1980 he was succeeded by roh another former general and close 
associate after presidential elections last december 
