<TEXT>
the prelate of hereford cathedral which is 
crumbling for lack of cash has provoked a heated dispute among 
churchmen and art experts by putting one of europes greatest 
medieval treasures on sale 
the 708yearold mappa mundi latin for map of the world has 
been kept in the cathedral for centuries and is to be auctioned by 
sothebys in london in june news reports put its value at more than 
45 million 
the sale announcement wednesday prompted a leading member of the 
cathedrals fundraising committee to resign in protest newspapers 
have published angry editorials against the sale and hereford town 
leaders have vowed to fight it 
the map shows historical events bible stories topography 
animals plants and 420 cities on a 6by4 sheet of vellum 
jerusalem is at the center of the map while hereford 144 miles 
northwest of london is drawn on one edge 
the controversy illuminates the dilemma faced by custodians of 
britains national heritage the 900yearold cathedral in hereford 
is one of many in need of cash but sales of treasures such as the 
mappa mundi threaten to put the nations historical heritage into 
the hands of foreign buyers and remove them from britain 
the dean of hereford the very rev peter haynes said in 
