<TEXT>
food and tobacco giant rjr nabisco inc on sunday 
extended its deadline for buyout offers after a potential new bidder 
said it was considering making a record offer of up to 266 billion 
the tentative proposal for rjr nabisco from a group led by the 
investment firm first boston corp and the pritzker family of 
chicago would be nearly double the biggest acquisition on record 
chevron corps 134 billion purchase of gulf oil corp in 1984 
the first boston proposal its first expression of interest in 
the consumer goods giant easily topped two sweetened offers made by 
rjr management and the buyout firm kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
rjr nabisco which is based in atlanta is the nations 19th 
biggest industrial company and the maker of hundreds of consumer 
items that range from jose cuervo tequila and salem cigarettes to 
life savers candy and milk bone dog snacks 
the offers disclosed sunday top all previous bids and a special 
rjr committee that is running the auction indicated that its 
decision to extend the bidding period could produce even higher 
offers 
due to the varying potential values and nature of the 
consideration offered in the two bids and the proposal and the 
varying terms conditions and contingencies associated with each 
the special committee determined not to make any recommendation at 
this time regarding any of the proposals said charles e hugel 
the committees chairman 
the fivemember committee of rjr nabiscos board of directors 
also said it would accept bids through nov 29 the panel had 
initially cut off bidding at 5 pm last friday 
the preliminary offer by the first bostonpritzker group would 
involve the acquisition in 1989 of rjrs tobacco business which 
accounts for about 40 percent of its annual sales followed by the 
installment sale of its food businesses 
first boston indicated the total consideration could range from 
98 to 110 cash a share plus securities and stock warrants valued 
at from 7 to 8 a share the warrants would entitle rjr 
shareholders to acquire up to 20 percent of the tobacco business 
at 118 a share the maximum possible offer from the group would 
be 266 billion 
the committee said the managementled group which is allied with 
the investment firms shearson lehman hutton inc and salomon 
brothers inc had raised its offer to 100 a share in cash for 175 
million of the companys 2253 million outstanding common shares 
the group said it would acquire the remaining shares for 56 
cash plus securities and common stock in the surviving company that 
it said would bring the total consideration to 100 a share the 
common stock would equal about 15 percent of the surviving companys 
outstanding shares according to the special committee 
the 100 a share offer values rjr at 225 billion the 
management groups previous offer had been for 92 a share or 207 
billion 
the new offer by kohlberg kravis which previously had offered 
90 a share or about 203 billion included 94 cash a share for 
about 178 million rjr nabisco shares with the remaining shares to 
be exchanged for preferred stock and securities the firm valued at 
94 a share giving its offer an indicated value of about 212 
billion 
management started the bidding a month ago when it announced it 
was considering a buyout offer and kohlberg kravis quickly entered 
the fray with a competing bid 
both parties submitted firm offers to the rjr committee by 
fridays deadline but they said late sunday they were undecided 
whether to make new offers 
