<TEXT>
under canadas parliamentary system voters choose a member of 
parliament from their district and dont vote directly for a party 
leader but three men symbolize their parties and stand to become 
prime minister 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
brian mulroney 
he led the progressive conservative party to a smashing victory 
in 1984 and became prime minister born in quebec of workingclass 
anglo parents he is the first bilingual native of that 
frenchspeaking province to lead his party 
the 49yearold mulroney eased smoothly from being a lawyer to 
his successful political career he is a strong emphatic public 
speaker 
his term was marked by general economic prosperity during which 
more than 1 million jobs were created and inflation remained stable 
at about 4 percent he was able to distance himself from eight 
cabinet ministers who resigned in successive scandals 
mulroney started the campaign hoping to persuade voters to return 
him as the most competent leader but the free trade pact he signed 
with president reagan quickly became the no 1 election issue 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
john turner 
the 59yearold turner inherited the liberal party leadership 
from pierre trudeau returning to politics as prime minister in 1984 
after eight years as a corporate lawyer 
he called an election two weeks later and was quickly ousted 
serving as prime minister only 79 days 
turner survived three internal attempts to oust him as liberal 
leader since 1984 he started this years campaign with the liberals 
in apparent disarray but forged ahead with his persistent attacks on 
the free trade agreement 
turner was born in england but came to canada as a child he was 
trudeaus finance minister from 1972 to 1975 and opponents call him 
the father of the modern canadian deficit for allowing government 
spending to rise substantially 
his home district is in vancouver british columbia 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ed broadbent 
a political science professor turned politician broadbent now 
has led his party in four national elections 
his integrity and personal credibility have helped the new 
democrats build their strongest national profile ever 
at the outset of the campaign there even was talk that they 
could finish second to become the official opposition yet the 
liberals revival appears to have pushed back the new democrats to 
their traditional thirdplace role 
broadbent 52 opposes the free trade agreement but tried to 
campaign on a broader platform on issues such as day care and the 
