<TEXT>
the us should help promote human rights in 
indonesia instead of turning its back on abuses for the sake of 
stability a private american human rights monitoring organization 
said 
asia watch said in a report released sunday that rights abuses 
including torture by police and political killings on the southeast 
asian archipelago continue but that the region is stable enough for 
the us to press its ally for more improvements 
neither the us embassy nor the us state department has 
placed promotion of human rights high on its agenda of foreign 
policy goals in indonesia asia watch said 
these issues demand increased attention among us officials 
because throughout the 1980s formal controls on political life 
have expanded and and a broadening crosssection of 
indonesian society has suffered politicallymotivated human rights 
violations including police torture and killings and lack of free 
press or speech 
asia watch attributed american silence to the persuasive power 
of the cult of stability among washington policymakers 
indonesian president suharto has deftly deflected criticism 
from abroad by continuing to evoke images of the instability 
associated with the tenure of president sukarno who ruled with 
communist support before suharto took power in 1965 
asia watch singled out the former portugese colony of east timor 
which indonesia annexed 13 years ago as an example of indonesias 
violation of human rights despite what the report said were 
improvements on the island residents continue to suffer daily 
violations of fundamental rights and indonesia fails to account 
for thousands of missing people believed killed in custody 
asia watch is affiliated with americas watch and helsinki watch 
which monitors compliance with the 1975 helsinki eastwest 
conference agreements on security and cooperation 
