<TEXT>
a federal judge has barred the city and state 
from cutting off services to 9000 retarded philadelphians who live 
at home saying the irrational decision threatened the 
recipients health and safety 
us district judge raymond j broderick issued a permanent 
injunction forbidding philadelphia and the state from eliminating 
vocational familysupport earlyintervention recreational and 
casemanagement services to mentally retarded people who live with 
their families 
in his ruling thursday the judge said that to deprive mentally 
retarded people of services they need for living and working would 
result in irreparable injury and cause serious regression to 
many he also said it would violate the equalprotection and 
dueprocess clauses of the constitution 
the order will continue until further notice from the court the 
judge said 
a projected 68 million shortage in state funds prompted the 
city in june to announced plans to reduce or eliminate services for 
mentally retarded philadelphians who live at home and are registered 
with the city for mentalretardation assistance services for 
mentally retarded people in statefunded group homes were not 
affected 
the judge ruled that the citys decision affecting services to 
the retarded living at home and not to those living in statefunded 
residences was arbitrary 
there has been a lack of judgment an irrational lack of 
fairness the constitution demands that defendants should have found 
a better way to resolve the problem broderick wrote 
the judge did not say whether the city or state must fund the 
services he did note however that the city has contributed 3 
million annually in excess of its 10 percent match 
state law requires the state to provide 90 percent of the funding 
for such services and counties are to pay 10 percent and provide the 
services themselves 
in july 32 people and the philadelphia police and fire 
association for handicapped children inc filed a classaction 
lawsuit against the city and state department of public welfare 
alleging that the citys mentally retarded were being denied their 
rights to lifelong community support 
broderick issued a temporary restraining order effective aug 1 
that prohibited a cutback in services and later extended it until 
last friday 
the attorney for the plaintiffs david ferleger hailed the 
ruling as a landmark 
no court has ever held that there is a guaranteed right to 
community services for people with retardation living at home 
ferleger said 
deputy city solicitor guy vilim said the city would review the 
opinion before deciding how to proceed 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

