<TEXT>
a judge has refused to set aside a 700000 
award against two newspapers saying they committed calculated 
misdeeds when they published a sources name after promising him 
confidentiality 
officials of the star tribune of minneapolis and the st paul 
pioneer press dispatch the states largest papers said they were 
not surprised by saturdays ruling and would appeal 
the case concerns a suit filed by dan cohen who claimed during 
trial in july that he lost his advertising job after the newspapers 
misrepresented and breached an oral contract they made to keep his 
name out of a politically sensitive story 
cohen had leaked court documents to reporters during the 1982 
gubernatorial campaign that revealed that marlene johnson a 
candidate for lieutenant governor had been arrested for shoplifting 
several years earlier 
cohen who worked for rival gubernatorial candidate wheelock 
whitney provided the information on the condition that he not be 
identified as the source 
editors at the newspapers testified that they overruled their 
reporters promises of anonymity because the public had the right to 
know the information came from the whitney campaign 
but hennepin county district judge franklin knoll ruled that the 
first amendments guarantee of freedom of the press did not shield 
the newspapers against cohens breach of contract claim 
the courts have made it clear that no first amendment interest 
exists in protecting news media from calculated misdeeds 
knolls memorandum said certainly the knowing and willful breach 
of a legally sufficient contract after hours of thought and 
discussion by corporate officers can fairly be characterized as a 
calculated misdeed 
knoll also dismissed the newspapers argument that a relationship 
between a reporter and a source is anything other than commercial 
the advertising war currently being waged by one newspaper 
against the other is ample evidence of the profit motive underlying 
their operations he said 
its our intent to appeal said john t henry publisher of 
the pioneer press dispatch we were hoping for a different 
outcome but this was not unanticipated 
tim j mcguire managing editor of the star tribune said his 
newspaper also will appeal the decision to the minnesota court of 
appeals 
