<TEXT>
lack of public accountability and an 
inefficient bureaucracy have created a nightmare of sinking ships 
rebels who escape from birthday parties and foodstocks that vanish 
some problems which have beset the philippines recently can be 
explained by bad luck including three tropical storms that killed 
more than 600 people in two weeks 
but others appear the result of appalling lack of organization 
resources and efficiency in president corazon aquinos 
administration lack of public accountability contributes to an 
atmosphere where accidents wait to happen 
that in turn may be undermining public confidence in government 
a recent survey by ateneo university of 1200 people nationwide 
found just 31 percent expected their lives to improve fortytwo 
percent expected conditions to remain the same and 17 percent said 
they would get worse 
it is not enough that the president sets the example wrote 
the philippine daily inquirer on the issue of accountability she 
should also find the strength and conviction to make examples of 
officials who do not measure up 
on nov 12 the alleged chief of the communist rebel army 
escaped the military says romulo kintanar 41 and his wife gloria 
38 walked away from a birthday party for the former stockade 
commandant 
acting stockade commander maj benjamin landrito offered as an 
excuse that he was asleep in his office at the time 
it was not the first security breach at the stockade 
kintanars host lt col robelito comilang was suspended last 
month when a rightwing officer jailed for a leading role in an 
august 1987 coup attempt reportedly walked through three doors that 
were supposed to be locked climbed the stockade wall and was 
fatally shot by guards 
mrs aquino today blamed the six military coup attempts that 
