more than 100 world leaders passed along 
greetings of peace monday in the 16th annual world hello day 
organized by two nebraska brothers 
president reagan and prince charles and princess diana were among 
the participants this year in the unofficial ritual designed to 
promote world peace with a series of simple hellos 
i guess when you get the heads of states of 100 countries 
together on anything you have really accomplished something 
cofounder michael mccormack said 
mccormack 36 was attending harvard university in 1973 when he 
and his brother brian 31 started world hello day in response to 
the growing tension in the middle east 
since then the annual event that involves greeting at least 10 
people in the name of peace has attracted international attention 
the brothers received letters of support this year from the 
leaders of 101 countries ranging from australia to zaire 
last week a letter arrived from the white house with a warm 
hello from reagan and on monday the brothers heard from the 
secretary general of the league of arab states 
others who have participated in world hello day include pope john 
paul ii mother teresa the late indian prime minister indira 
gandhi bishop desmond tutu solidarity leader lech walesa the late 
egyptian president anwar sadat costa rican president oscar arias 
sanchez queen elizabeth ii and former presidents gerald ford and 
jimmy carter 
mccormack said he has received thousands of letters this year 
from everyday people but it is the notes from famous leaders that 
draw the most attention 
the president of beijing university in china told me that one 
of the things world hello day does is mobilize people to act in a 
specific way to promote peace it gives them a taste of what it is 
like to participate in that process mccormack said 
letters have arrived from prince charles and princess diana 
olivia de havilland billy graham jim henson charlton heston lee 
iacocca richard leakey james a michener jack nicklaus arnold 
palmer luciano pavarotti stevie wonder and pele 
you talk about a grassroots movement that goes from the ground 
up mccormack said what we have done is work from the other 
direction from the crowns of the trees down to the roots people 
are interested when they say their own head of state has written a 
letter and supports world hello day 
mccormack who devotes all his time to the annual event said he 
doesnt have much interest in trying to gain official national 
status for world hello day in the united states 
i think what we would like to do is keep it a day that becomes 
a special day because people want to make it a special day on their 
own not because it is an official holiday he said 
