<TEXT>
the federal reserve board on monday proposed a 
rule imposing tighter restrictions on the ability of statechartered 
banks to acquire nonbanking subsidiaries 
the rule proposed by a 61 vote with board member martha seger 
dissenting would require that the approximately 7000 
statechartered banks owned by holding companies get the feds 
permission before estabishing real estate insurance and other 
nonbanking subsidiaries 
proponents of the rule say some states have moved aggressively to 
authorize new activities without regard for bank safety and 
soundness opponents say the federal reserve should not seek more 
power over state banks 
regulation y adopted in 1971 has allowed state banks to 
purchase nonbank firms without fed approval under the bank holding 
company act 
the change could be adopted in three to six months it would 
exempt nonbank businesses already owned by statechartered banks 
although federal reserve vice chairman manuel johnson asked the fed 
staff to solicit comment on the possibility of requiring divestiture 
of such activities 
a recent federal court ruling requires nationallychartered banks 
to receive federal reserve permission before acquiring a nonbank 
subsidiary the decision is being appealed and the federal reserves 
staff said it would propose rules for national banks later 
</TEXT>
