a marbleandbrass monument commemorating 
john f kennedys visits to the waterbury area has been found nearly 
25 years after it was cast and stored to await the opening of the 
presidential library in massachusetts 
robert carroll a member of the committee that commissioned the 
monument in 1964 in the wake of the presidents assassination said 
monday that he discovered the monument in a wolcott high school 
storage room in september 
he said he didnt tell anyone about the discovery until recently 
so the news would coincide with the 25th anniversary of the 
assassination on tuesday 
the wolcott residents who commissioned the monument intended to 
send it to the john f kennedy presidential library on the 
university of massachusetts campus in bostons dorchester section 
i think once they at the library see this its really the 
kind of a monument its probably valued at 4000 to 5000 that 
belongs there carroll said 
the white marble plaque with a brass plate the cost of which was 
underwritten by the scovill manufacturing co and chase brass amp 
copper co both of waterbury memorializes kennedys visits to 
waterbury on the eve of the 1960 election and in 1962 
an estimated 50000 people greeted kennedy on nov 6 1960 at 3 
am in downtown waterbury wolcott borders waterbury and carroll 
said many of its residents hail from the bluecollar city 
the monument bears the presidential seal and a quotation from a 
speech kennedy delivered on his second visit to waterbury on oct 
17 1962 
carroll said a blacktie ball in waterbury in november 1964 was 
held to remember the late presidents promise his mother rose 
kennedy attended carroll said 
the problem in 1964 was that the kennedy library had not been 
built yet so the plaque had to be stored somewhere until the 
library was complete he recalled 
carroll said he suggested keeping it in a closet in the high 
school the monument was promptly forgotten he said 
he said he had intended to bring it to the library on the 
assassination anniversary but the librarys curator and onetime 
kennedy assistant david powers reminded him that the family 
doesnt prefer to remember that date instead carroll said he 
will take the plaque to boston next year on may 29 the late 
presidents birthday 
powers said the library will accept the plaque but he couldnt 
say whether or not it will be displayed 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

