<TEXT>
canada the worlds secondlargest country 
sprawling across six time zones forbids broadcasters from spreading 
election results while polls remain open 
that means election coverage starts at 8 pm local time in each 
zone as the polls close unlike the us system where the pacific 
coast receives network coverage while voting continues 
weve got six time zones thats why weve got to be very 
cautious said jacques mackay of the federal elections canada 
agency of course its very difficult today in the age of 
comunications to limit it but its still done 
mackay said in a telephone interview from ottawa that the law 
prohibits broadcasters from talking about election results while 
polls remain open in any particular time zone 
its still possible to phone somebody in the east and say 
whats going on bazay said 
the majority of canadas population lives in quebec and ontario 
which are on eastern standard time those two provinces account for 
107 million of the 175 million voters registered for mondays 
election and 174 of the 295 seats in the house of commons 
that leads to complaints from those who live farther west 
especially british columbia which has 32 seats where polls close 
three hours later 
its very simple david bazay executive producer of the 
public canadian broadcasting corps network news said when asked 
to explain the system we do it every day as a matter of course 
our national news basically has five editions 
election programming for newfoundland where polls close at 630 
pm est can start in the central studio in toronto and be 
broadcast regionally the atlantic coast of nova scotia new 
brunswick and prince edward island is added an hour later then 
quebec and ontario 
we have a network we can put the entire national network 
together or parts of it together bazay said as the polls 
close across the country we simply put on election coverage 
its not complicated at all 
the private canadian tv network also was planning coverage 
starting at 8 pm local time global was not starting its coverage 
until about 1015 pm after the conclusion of a national hockey 
league game between st louis and toronto 
satellite and cable television are increasingly available to 
canadian households pierre pontbriand spokesman for the canadian 
radio and television commission said it was the responsibility of 
each satellite and cable licensee to comply with the election law 
