presidentelect george bush should cancel some 
weapons and look for other pentagon savings as part of the effort to 
control the defense budget a congressional agency said monday 
the general accounting office in one of a series of reports on 
issues facing bush when he takes office jan 20 noted that even 
though each of the services says it needs many billions of dollars 
more to complete its modernization and expansion programs the 
current 300 billion defense budget isnt likely to be increased for 
the forseeable future 
current pentagon plans include programs which would cost about 
200 billion more than the defense department can expect to 
receive during the fiveyear period which ends in 1992 the 
congressional watchdog agency said 
bush and the democraticcontrolled congress need to take a number 
of actions to reduce future defense expenditures the gao said 
those include 
reducing and realigning planned programs in so doing cancel 
marginal systems and delay systems not ready for production it 
did not give examples 
seeking common missions in the past for example we have 
developed a variety of systems landbased to aircraft to attack 
tanks 
carefully assessing the longterm impact of planned weapons the 
gao said that recalling four world war ii battleships from mothballs 
was cheaper than building four new warships but operating three of 
the ships will cost 150 million this year and require about 4600 
personnel 
rethinking americas farflung network of worldwide commitments 
the rising costs of our worldwide commitments in the absence of 
increased burdensharing by our allies may simply be unaffordable 
the new administration also needs to take steps to try to end the 
series of weapons purchasing scandals and high prices for spare 
parts 
one improvement would be in the pentagon office which oversees 
what is supposed to be the realistic testing of weapons the gao 
said 
the usefulness of the current testing system has been limited 
because of insufficient resources to conduct testing deferrel of 
certain critical tests until after the production decision failure 
to simulate realistic battlefield conditions during testing and 
acceptance of products which do not meet the test criteria it 
said 
