<TEXT>
a computer chip maker has adopted a strict 
nosmoking policy in its texas plants in a policy shift that some 
predict will sweep the us semiconductor industry 
the new rules which take effect jan 2 apply to all texas 
employees of advanced micro devices inc 2200 in austin and 900 
in san antonio 
its kind of a pilot project in texas said david frink a 
local spokesman for the californiabased company 
the company plans to remove ash trays and cigarette machines and 
has encouraged workers to join smoking cessation classes designed 
by the american cancer society 
employees previously were allowed to smoke in designated areas 
although never in the clean rooms where delicate computer chips 
are made 
frink said the company revised its smoking policy to eliminate a 
potential source of chipdestroying contaminants a speck of dust or 
smoke particle can block part of a microscopic circuit and ruin a 
chip 
he said it also responds to recent evidence linking nonsmokers 
health hazards to secondhand smoke 
the company chose texas for the experiment because its operations 
are smaller here than in california frink told the austin 
americanstatesman in addition chips made in texas are among its 
most sensitive 
other chipmakers predicted more companies would follow suit 
stan victor a spokesman for texas instruments in dallas said 
the company discourages smoking but has not yet gone as far as 
advanced micro devices 
texas instruments offers smoking cessation classes to employees 
and their spouses victor said and asks clean room employees who 
smoke during breaks to rinse their mouths with water and wait at 
least five minutes before reentering the chipmaking area 
scott wyman a spokesman for international business machines 
corp said the company has banned smoking in some of its newer 
manufacturing buildings but it allows designated smoking areas in 
compliance with an austin ordinance 
the manager of contamination engineering for sematech keith 
dillenbeck said advanced micro devices policy likely will spread 
through the industry 
there is a trend in that direction dillenbeck said 
dillenbeck said technical journals have indicated smoke can 
linger in the mouth and lungs as well as cling to clothes and hair 
as long as two hours after smoking 
as a result he said smokers in the clean room may generate as 
many as 10 times more particles than nonsmokers 
</TEXT>
