<TEXT>
us trade representative clayton yeutter 
announced an investigation monday into the way japan runs its 
building trades to see if it includes unfair practices that hurt or 
threaten us industry 
he said the action was required by the trade act that president 
reagan signed into law in august 
the investigation will cover japanese acts policies and and 
practices that may be barriers to us architectural engineering 
and construction services and consulting services related to them 
yeutters statement said the us government will consult with the 
government of japan and seek advice from business committees and the 
public 
a finding of unfair practices could lead to us retaliation 
last year japan opened construction on the huge kansai 
international airport to foreign bidders after a long dispute on 
access for us companies the airport will serve osaka 
the announcement of the investigation came as presidentelect 
george bush was advised to make vigorous use of the new powers that 
congress has given the president to get satisfaction from other 
countries in trade disputes 
the advice came from the general accounting office which has 
prepared a series of brief reports on important issues for the 
transition to the new presidency which begins on jan 20 
a report on trade released monday said the office had found many 
instances when a followup was needed to get the benefits of an 
international trade agreement it added that delaying tactics and 
slow dispute settlements have often frustrated efforts to get 
satisfaction but the new trade act strengthens the us hand 
failure to gain timely satisfaction can now trigger a 
unilateral us response the report said 
the new administration should show strong resolve to vigorously 
use these new powers 
the report was submitted by comptroller general charles a 
bowsher the head of the office to congress and to the us trade 
representative designate bush has not yet appointed a successor 
to yeutter who is expected to leave with reagans administration 
which goes out of office jan 20 
the report does not specify which new powers it means other 
governments have said they were worried that the president now has 
additional power to protect us industry against competiion one 
new provision of the new law permits him to specify what he 
considers high priority unfair trade practises and to start action 
toward retaliation while trying to get a settlement by negotiation 
another provision permits him to rule that a country denying 
internationally recognized rights to labor can be considered as 
engaging in an unfair trade practise and to retaliate against its 
trade 
the gao complained of defects in efforts to promote us exports 
it said the commerce department has chosen questionable trade 
promotion events and has been active in countries with little or no 
potential for buying more us goods it did not specify the 
countries 
it criticized as largely symbolic the controls put on exports 
to further us foreign policy objectives as distinct from controls 
which have security objectives 
when these controls are symbolic they do not prevent the 
targeted country from getting the controlled products from other 
countries the report said 
instead their costs are borne by american businesses in the 
form of export sales lost to firms in other countries 
the report did not specify either the countries targeted by the 
us controls or their suppliers one country where us exports 
are controlled because of us foreign policy is south africa where 
japanese and west european suppliers have replaced many exports that 
can now no longer be shppied by americans 
