at a meeting where more than 20 percent 
of the leadership was ousted the central council of the hungarian 
trade unions said monday it no longer automatically supports 
government austerity measures 
while duly respecting independent government decisions it 
said in a statement the unions will not assume responsibility 
for them not actually having participated in that decisionmaking 
process 
the central council which has a membership of about 220 ousted 
45 council members and appointed 37 new members the state news 
agency mti reported the meeting defined the fundamental tasks of 
trade unions as protecting and representing the specific interests 
of workers 
reorganization and the change in basic policy were seen as a 
reaction to an increasing trend toward installing new independent 
unions in communist hungary a spinoff development of economic and 
social reforms here 
mti said the central council demanded that the government follow 
a firm antiinflation policy and called for earliest implementation 
of wage reform 
living standards have fallen for months mainly because of price 
increases and a new tax system and inflation is running at about 16 
percent 
on the central councils list of basic issues to be discussed 
with the government at their next session nov 28 are living 
standards including real wages and income employment and social 
policy the agency said 
speakers at the council meeting were said to have stressed that 
the government must declare a partnership with unions as befits 
discussions between equal partners 
some speakers not identified by mti said it was not true that 
the trade union movement had lost the confidence of workers but 
admitted that some individuals some measures and certain methods 
have shaken the confidence of the membership 
it said said some speakers denounced as shocking unspecified 
curbs on trade union rights there was no elaboration 
</TEXT>
