<TEXT>
staying in touch is what the feelies are all 
about 
with their audience and with their music 
id rather appeal to 500 people for the right reasons than 
5000 for the wrong reasons its really what you mean to people 
group member glenn mercer said 
as for their music mercer said were reducing it to its basic 
element pure energy and spirit no intellect involved at all 
really 
you dont want to make it seem that its really being thought 
about you dont write a song about people being fascinated it just 
sort of comes out of you no preconceived ideas 
on their third album only life the feelies stick to the 
same unfettered approach the lyrics are terse like telegrams 
every word counts the singing is deliberately flat stripped of all 
emotion and irony the listener is left to wonder if such words as 
nothing matters and what if it did are to be taken at face 
value or a criticism of that attitude 
all of our songs are open to interpretation mercer said 
id much prefer that to saying what the songs about i think you 
failed in a way if you have to say what a songs about it really 
takes away something from the song 
the arrangements keep to the basic rock n roll combination of 
drums bass and guitars mercer said the feelies were attracted to 
the stooges the modern lovers and the mc5 groups more interested 
in emotion than fancy chord structures 
it was a combination one being that theyre pretty simple 
bands they gave you the feeling you didnt have to take years of 
music lessons didnt have to buy really expensive equipment you 
could make music on a personal level another thing they were cult 
bands nobody else knew about them 
bill million who cowrites the feelies songs with mercer liked 
the spontaneous feel of those groups 
the music had a lot of energy he said the stooges sounded 
like the guitar player just got a fender a fuzz box and an 
amplifier for christman and just recorded the album two weeks 
later 
but that changed in the 70s 
then it got away from that bands like emerson lake and palmer 
and yes just the opposite really 
the feelies were high school students in haledon nj when the 
group was formed in 1976 the original lineup consisted of mercer 
and million on guitars dave weckerman on drums and percussion and 
john j on bass 
they made their debut at manchester high school in haledon the 
following year not too successfully million remembered 
the audience wasnt getting into what we were doing between 
breaks they asked us if they could use the instruments and play 
stuff the audience actually wanted to hear then we started playing 
cbgbs and maxs kansas city 
and then the feelies caught on in 1978 they were called the 
best underground band in new york in a village voice cover story 
our audience went from about 12 to 600 people million 
recalled 
it seemed like a perfect fit when the feelies signed with stiff 
records and released their debut album crazy rhythms in 1980 
here was the best underground band and the ultimate new wave 
record label the home of elvis costello graham parker and nick 
lowe 
the feelies found out however that stiff had the same priority 
as the major record companies the bottom line 
they lectured us on how to write a hit single it was like a 
scene out of a movie mercer said 
there were no hit singles and despite excellent reviews crazy 
rhythms was a commercial failure and the feelies disbanded in 
1981 not because they wanted to mercer noted 
we didnt anticipate not playing for that long the gigs got 
further and further apart we werent thinking in turns of a 
finality we tend to go where things lead we got involved in doing 
different things not wanting to get involved with another bad 
experience 
but the feelies were not forgotten film director jonathan demme 
had seen the band play at the whiskey a go go in los angeles and 
suggested that mercer and million write the soundtrack for susan 
seidelmans smithereens released in 1982 
he was a fan of the band we kept in touch million said 
the feelies regrouped in 1983 with brenda sauter on bass stanley 
demeski on drums and weckerman moving to percussion in 1986 they 
released the good earth on coyote records 
the same year the feelies appeared in demmes hit film 
something wild performing a cover of the monkees im a 
believer at a high school reunion 
it was fun a lot of hard work but primarily fun they made us 
comfortable mercer said 
but the feelies are not looking to be a fun band theyre not 
interested in being fashionable they seek connection with their 
fans through music 
the people there are just there for the music its not like 
going to the disco and getting dressed and making the scene 
mercer said 
added million there isnt a scene to make 
</TEXT>
