<TEXT>
with little hope of winning the 
presidency venezuelas minor political parties are seeking to make 
inroads in congress in national elections dec 4 
they are counting on a major defection from the nations two main 
parties 
the small parties acknowledge that their 23 presidential 
candidates including a handful of leftists a witchdoctor some 
retired military officers and a former central bank president 
dont have a chance in the presidential balloting 
but they say widespread voter discontent with the governments 
accion democratica ad and the main opposition party copei will 
be shown in splitticket voting that could yield a congress of 182 
deputies and 44 senators with no single party in control 
it would mean a major change in recent venezuelan voting patterns 
with longerterm effects as the nation slowly decentralizes its 
political system they said 
people are not happy with ad or copei but they recognize their 
candidates have the best chance to win the presidency but their 
true electoral preference will be shown in the congressional vote 
said freddy munoz secretary general of movement to socialism mas 
venezuelas third largest electoral force 
most political analysts agree small parties the larger of which 
are left of center are likely to post gains in congress 
they note that voters associate the countrys economic slump 
about to enter its eighth year with centerright copei and 
centerleft ad 
the crisis caused by low oil prices began under a copei 
administration and has continued under current ad administration of 
president jaime lusinchi 
polls indicate that while over 75 percent of the electorate 
express a preference for either ads frontrunning candidate carlos 
andres perez or copeis eduardo fernandez only half the eligible 
voters have decided to vote for one of the two parties 
congressional slates 
the disaffection has been exacerbated by unexciting campaigns ad 
politicians bemoan the triumphalism of the partys candidates 
who have depended on perezs popularity to sweep them into office 
rather than campaigning for themselves 
mas on the other hand adopted a campaign strategy that 
deemphasized the campaign of its presidential candidate former 
guerrilla teodoro petkoff in favor of its congressional candidates 
the ticketsplitting would be a major change from recent 
venezuelan voting patterns 
in the six elections since 1958 ad and copei alternated in the 
presidency since 1973 the two parties combined have garnered not 
less than 88 percent of the presidential vote 
minor parties had just 27 seats in the last 200member house of 
deputies including 10 from mas ad had 113 seats and copei 60 and 
some of the small parties ally themselves with ad or copei 
but even if mas gets around 15 percent of the congressional vote 
as some analysts predict it likely would have little impact on the 
direction of venezuelan politics in the short term 
with venezuelas overwhelmingly strong executive branch 
congressional action is normally limited to making minor adjustments 
to presidential initiatives 
but ticketsplitting could mean a revival of mas and the ability 
of small national or regional parties to survive until the 
presidential election in 1993 
their survival takes on more significance as the big parties 
reluctantly allow some decentralization of power to take place 
