<TEXT>
why use a book to teach children about the life 
cycle of the butterfly when they can witness metamorphosis 
one is an aesthetic hairraising experience that is just 
absolutely dramatic beyond belief the other all it is is just 
reading another set of symbols said francis m pottenger iii 
director of science projects for the curriculum research and 
development group at the university of hawaii 
substituting words for natures wonders unfortunately is what 
most of science has been over the years said pottenger you 
destroy science that way you literally destroy science by putting 
it into that form 
pottenger 60 a former high school science teacher has 
developed a teaching program that replaces books with real world 
lessons developmental approaches in science and health integrates 
science health and technology with subjects such as literature and 
social studies 
dash is the elementary equivalent to his foundational approaches 
in science teaching a middle school program used by more than 1200 
districts nationwide 
he had started fast in 1966 with money from the university of 
hawaii and the state to take advantage of hawaiis natural 
museum environment it was introduced in hawaii in 1970 and spread 
to the mainland in 1976 being tailored to reflect each districts 
needs and natural surroundings 
we wanted to look at the real world in which the child lived 
rather than the textbook world pottenger said 
in dash instead of lecturing on the importance of sanitation 
for example teachers are encouraged to whip up some germy goo 
out of cocoa and cooking oil that children can dip their fingers 
into while listening to a poem or two 
there once was a terrible germ who was long and looked like a 
worm his favorite trick was to get people sick so theyd lie on 
their back and squirm 
such strategies work wonders said ann baldwin taylor director 
of the childrens school at carnegie mellon university a campus 
laboratory school for research in child development 
if language arts and math and science and younameit are all 
together all of a sudden the kids click click click she 
said snapping her fingers oh i get it i understand and i can 
use it here here here and here 
kindergarten teacher gloria cannon whose laboratory school is 
affiliated with the state university of new york at buffalo is just 
as enthusiastic about what she calls dashs whole world and 
capturingthemoment approach it allows for the individual 
its not this is the right answer or the wrong answer there are 
many right answers for the same thing and many ways to solve one 
particular problem cannon said 
the trick is getting students to see how science touches their 
lives 
once the child understands and can use the material to 
understand their world around them theyre hooked for life ms 
taylor said its when the child doesnt understand that you 
lose them they just turn it off 
dash was incorporated this fall into kindergarten and firstgrade 
curriculums at 10 laboratory schools which are the same as any 
other school except for affiliation with universities course 
materials are expected to be ready for grades two through six in 
1991 it eventually will be offered like fast to public schools 
willing to buy the material and have their teachers trained by a 
special team of instructors 
the major problem has been that elementary teachers generally 
have been frightened by science because they are fearful theyre 
going to make a mistake pottenger said its much easier to 
return to the textbook which gives all the proper answers 
with dash he said teachers look not so much at textbook 
answers but real phenomenon the phenomenon tell you whether or not 
you have actually a proper interpretation 
