an alaska beverage producer hoping for 
spirited competition with the soviets has begun bottling vodka made 
with glacier water 
mark wilson president of alaska mountaintop spirits co said 
the attakiska vodka that his firm began bottling in november will be 
sold intially in alaska and in eastern states with sales later 
expected to reach other parts of the united states plus some pacific 
rim nations 
wilson said he expects an immediate monthly demand for 2000 to 
3000 cases of the new vodka three percent of total sales are 
targeted for alaska he said 
while people are on the whole drinking less they are more 
discriminating in what they are drinking wilson said todays 
consumer is more sophisticated and is willing to spend the few extra 
dollars it takes to buy the best vodka available 
he also said he is relying on the alaska mystique to draw people 
to the product for a firsttime sip 
the mystique and character of alaska will be key to breaching 
the stronghold of the established market leaders wilson said 
the production process is described as one that takes the soviet 
method a step further through use of the pure and distinctive 
glacier waters available in alaska and through a special finishing 
process 
wilson said he has been working with a stamford conn marketing 
firm to launch the vodka his other products include alaska bottled 
water and bagged beverage ice chipped from alaska glaciers 
he said the anchorage vodka plant is a 500000 highspeed 
facility built to produce more than 5 million bottles of vodka 
annually he is offering two sizes with suggested retail prices of 
12 and 16 the bottles bear a label with an eagle and a star and 
carry a pewtercolored seal stamped with the words made in 
alaskaattakiska 
wilson said that by years end he expects to operate with two 
shifts involving a total of 21 full and parttime employees 
the vodka market is huge he said and the percentage of us 
demand met with imported versions of the drink has been increasing 
in recent years 
educated as a zoologist wilson 40 said he got into the 
beverage business after he and a partner mick mckay started a 
business in the field of water treatment 
with much of that enterprise related to the oil industry 
activity for the men dwindled as the oil boom flattened wilson 
said he and mckay had been developing a consumer division in their 
firm wetco inc and those operations carried them through the bad 
times in the petroleum industry he said 
