<TEXT>
the european economic communitys competition 
commissioner said monday it was essential that the 12 eec states 
forge a joint merger control policy 
national laws are simply not adequate to deal with crossborder 
mergers in particular those which may have an effect upon the 
community as a whole commissioner peter sutherland said in a 
speech 
last week eec states agreed to empower the eec commission to 
consider corporate mergers in advance and maybe block them 
but the commission is seeking the power to rule on mergers 
exceeding a billion european currency units which are worth about 
119 billion in annual revenue britain france and west germany 
want that limit raised 
urging speedy adoption of a merger control policy sutherland 
said differing national rules on mergers which may lead to 
conflicting decisions 
this is a severe handicap for the companies concerned who are 
entitled to expect greater legal certainty and more rapid 
procedures he said 
he said companies increasingly view the eec countries as their 
home market it is now widely acknowledged that if the economic 
objectives underpinning the single market strategy are to be 
achieved a streamlined community merger control mechanism must be 
available 
sutherland spoke at a conference organized by the london daily 
financial times on eecs plans to knock down trade barriers among 
its member nations by dec 31 1992 
he said while the eec members adopted a modest airline 
deregulation plan in 1987 we have to go further he said the 
commission has begun drafting proposals for a second stage of 
liberalization 
these will deal with ending curbs on capacity and prices and 
freeing air carriers of the system of slot allocation at airports 
that now favors major airlines at the expense of smaller 
competitors sutherland said 
he said the commission also planned to tackle air transportation 
agreements between eec nations and other countries 
there is now a good case for the negotiation of air service 
agreements between the community and other nations the present 
network of bilateral agreements has resulted in an unduly rigid 
international air transport system he said 
