ltv corp reported on monday a thirdquarter net 
loss of 124 billion which company officials attributed largely to 
chapter 11related special charges 
a change in accounting principles for postemployment medical and 
life insurance benefits also had a negative impact on results 
officials of the diversified company said 
the loss compares with a net profit of 1097 million or 91 
cents a share in the third quarter of 1987 
ltv officials said the special charges and the accounting change 
are important elements in moving the company toward its chapter 11 
reorganization 
because ltv is in chapter 11 we believe it is appropriate for 
the company to record all its liabilities including the liability 
for these postemployment benefits so that they may be 
appropriately dealt with in the reorganization process said 
raymond hay ltvs chairman and chief executive officer 
angela tese a bankruptcy specialist for cole amp deitz in new 
york said mondays announcement of a negative net worth was not a 
good signal for the company 
theyll have to prove to the bankruptcy court that the plan 
is feasible tese said they are going to have to be able to 
demonstrate to the court that they are healthy enough and that they 
wont have to reorganize again sometime soon 
the thirdquarter special charges total 134 billion ost of 
which is noncash they include 
950 million for chapter 11 creditors claims 
350 million for a reduction of assets and other anticipated 
costs in the divesture of ltv steel cos bar business as well as 
additional costs incurred in the rationalization of other steel 
facilities 
41 million for the writeoff of goodwill recorded in connection 
with the companys 1983 acquisition of sierra research corp 
without the two elements ltv said its net income would have been 
1322 million for the third quarter and 4537 million for the 
first nine months of the year that would have compared with 1097 
million and 3620 million for the respective periods in 1987 
the change in accounting principle alters the method of 
accounting for postemployment medical and life insurance benefits 
and resulted in a onetime noncash charge of 226 billion 
recorded as of last jan 1 
the accounting method adopted by ltv recognizes the 
postemployment medical and life insurance benefits earned by all of 
the companys retirees and active employees hay said 
previously these costs were recognized only as they were paid 
the change in accounting principle reduced operating income by 
321 million for the third quarter and 982 million for the 
ninemonth period 
for the first nine months ltv reported a net loss of 325 
billion which company officials also attributed to the special 
charges and accounting change that compared with a net profit of 
3620 million or 307 a share in the same ninemonth period of 
1987 
